quest_title: The S.I. unit of radioactivity is
explanation_txt:
The Becquerel (Bq) is the SI derived unit of radioactivity. One becquerel is defined as the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second. The becquerel is therefore equivalent to an inverse second, s−1.

1 Rutherford = 106 disintegration per second i.e. 1060 Bq = 1 MBq

1 Curie = 3.7*1010 disintegration per second i.e 37*109 Bq = 37 GBq

Roentgen is a unit to measure exposure of \(X\)-rays and \(\gamma\)-rays.

quest_title: Total number of four digit odd numbers that can be formed using 0, 1, 2, 3, 5, 7 are
explanation_txt:
0, 1, 2, 3, 5, 7 : Six digits

The last place can be filled in by 1, 3, 5, 7. i.e, 4 ways as the number is to be odd.

We have to fill in the remaining 3 places of the 4 digit number. Since repetition is allowed each place can be filled in 6 ways. Hence the 3 place can be filled in \(6^3 = 216\) ways. So, total number of ways \( = 4 \times 216 = 864 \)

The numbers starting from \(0\) and ending with odd digit are: \( 1 \times 6^2 \times 4= 144 \)

So, the total number of numbers is : \(864 - 144 = 720 \)

So, the domain is \( (-\infty,-a] \cup [a, \infty) \)

This is equivalent to \( \mathbb{R} - (-a,a) \)

quest_title: A stone projected with a velocity \(u\) at an angle \(\theta\) with the horizontal reaches maximum height \(H _ { 1 . }\) When it is projected with velocity \(u\) at an angle \(\left( \cfrac { \pi } { 2 } - \theta \right)\) with the horizontal, it reaches maximum height \(H _ { 2 } .\) The relation between the horizontal range \(R\) of the projectile, \(H _ { 1 }\) and \(H _ { 2 }\) is
explanation_txt:
\(H _ { 1 } = \cfrac { u ^ { 2 } \sin ^ { 2 } \theta } { 2 g } \text { and } H _ { 2 } = \cfrac { u ^ { 2 } \sin ^ { 2 } ( 90 - \theta ) } { 2 g } = \cfrac { u ^ { 2 } \cos ^ { 2 } \theta } { 2 g }\)

\(H _ { 1 } H _ { 2 } = \cfrac { u ^ { 2 } \sin ^ { 2 } \theta } { 2 g } \times \cfrac { u ^ { 2 } \cos ^ { 2 } \theta } { 2 g } = \cfrac { \left( u ^ { 2 } \sin 2 \theta \right) ^ { 2 } } { 16 g ^ { 2 } } = \cfrac { R ^ { 2 } } { 16 }\)

\(\therefore R = 4 \sqrt { H _ { 1 } H _ { 2 } }\)
